          "body": "The chapter closes with a call-and-response exchange that functions as a script for repentance. A voice of weeping is heard on the bare heights (3:21) — the same bare heights where the sin was committed (3:2) have now become the location of lamentation. God responds with the summons and the promise in a single breath: 'Return, O faithless sons, I will heal your faithlessness' (3:22) — the invitation and the provision are simultaneous. The people's response (3:22b-25) is a model confession: it identifies the true God ('You are the LORD our God'), renounces the false ('the hills are a deception'), locates salvation exclusively in Yahweh ('in the LORD our God is the salvation of Israel'), names the specific cost of idolatry ('the shameful thing has consumed the labor of our fathers'), prostrates in shame ('let us lie down in our shame'), and makes the confession corporate and chronologically comprehensive ('from our youth even to this day'). Commentators from Calvin to Lundbom have noted that this closing liturgy is not merely descriptive of some future moment — it is prescriptive for Judah now. Jeremiah has provided the words; the question is whether the audience will say them."
